en_835888_0	Pakistani Foreign Minister Mahmood Qureshi met President Gotabhaya Rajapaksa today.
en_835888_1	Their meeting took place at the President’s Office.
en_835888_2	Expressing his greeting and that of his Government to the President, the Foreign Minister announced Pakistan’s intention to strengthen bilateral relations with respect to economic development, trade, security cooperation and regional cooperation between the two countries.
en_835888_3	The Pakistani Foreign Minister said that his Government was willing TO jointly work with Sri Lanka to develop the Buddhist Heritage and safeguard it.
en_835888_4	He invited the President to undertake a visit to Pakistan.
en_835888_5	Expressing his views President Gotabhaya Rajapaksa said it is important to develop trade and investment rather than looking for financial assistance.
en_835888_6	The President also expressed views with respect to the export of beetle to Pakistan.
en_835888_7	Gotabhaya Rajapaksa said that he expected the support of the Pakistani Government to contain the drugs racket as well as on the battle against Islam extremism.
en_835888_8	Pakistani Foreign Ministry Director General Dr. Mohamed Faizal and Pakistani Acting High Commissioner in Sri Lanka Thanvir Ahmed joined in the discussion.
en_835888_9	Meanwhile, Pakistan’s Foreign Minister Mahmood Qureshi met his Sri Lankan counterpart Dinesh Gunawardena and engaged in talks.
en_835888_10	The meeting between the two Foreign Ministers took place at the Foreign Ministry.
en_835888_11	Foreign Secretary Ravinatha Ariyasinghe joined them in this discussion.
en_835888_12	After the meeting the Pakistani Foreign Minister expressed views to the media.
en_835888_13	The Pakistani Foreign Minister said that he is glad to be the first Foreign Minister to be visiting the Sri Lanka after the new Government assuming office.
en_835888_14	He said he had a fruitful discussion with his Sri Lankan counterpart.
en_835888_15	They discussed further strengthening the long term ties between the two countries.
en_835888_16	He said he invited the Sri Lankan Minister to visit Pakistan.
en_835888_17	Pakistan expects to work mutually with the new Government.
